Migration services, and the Snow family.

The R tells you the strategy; these services move the bytes. A-W-S Application Migration Service, M-G-N, formerly CloudEndure, is the modern lift-and-shift tool, and it replaces the deprecated Server Migration Service. You install a lightweight agent on each source server, physical, VMware, Hyper-V, or cross-cloud, and M-G-N continuously block-level replicates the disks to a low-cost staging area on E-B-S. When you're ready, you launch test instances or cut over, and the source machine becomes a byte-identical E-C-2 instance in minutes.

A-W-S Database Migration Service, D-M-S, handles the database tier. Homogeneous migrations, like Oracle to R-D-S Oracle, keep the same schema. Heterogeneous migrations, like Oracle to Aurora PostgreSQL, use the Schema Conversion Tool, the S-C-T, to translate the schema and stored procedures, and then D-M-S streams the data with ongoing change-data-capture so source and target stay in sync until cutover, for near-zero-downtime moves. And A-W-S DataSync is network-based bulk file transfer, from on-premises N-F-S, S-M-B, H-D-F-S, or object storage into S3, E-F-S, or F-S-x, with a managed agent, scheduling, and integrity checks.

When the network simply won't do, A-W-S ships you hardware, the Snow family. Snowcone is small, rugged, eight terabytes, and battery-powered, for IoT and field collection, with some on-device compute. Snowball Edge is the workhorse, in a Storage Optimized variant of about eighty terabytes, or a Compute Optimized variant with more v-C-P-U and G-P-U for edge compute. And Snowmobile is a literal forty-five-foot shipping container delivering a hundred petabytes per unit, for exabyte-scale data-centre evacuations. The rule of thumb: if shipping a Snowball is faster than your network link can sustain over the migration window, ship it; five hundred terabytes on a hundred-megabit link would take roughly four hundred sixty days online. Encryption is end-to-end with K-M-S keys you control.
